748634ABBAC74DD1BE4801CB63C1D409.description:
Identify and describe strategies
used to complete increasingly difficult
puzzles (for example, when completing
a floor puzzle, working on the edges
first).

DADBCF94460E4A13B085916D0691D11C.description:
Begin to explain how a mathematical
problem was solved (“I saw that there
was always a blue flower after a red
flower so I knew to put a blue one
next.” “I counted four friends who didn’t
have crackers so I got four more.”).

C57E4EF2DBB5478A83C2CA9311A378F7.description:
Use drawing, writing, and
concrete materials to represent and
communicate a variety of mathematical
ideas (draw shapes to represent
pattern; stack different-colored blocks
to represent classmates’ answers to a
survey question).

757928D011AF461E8FC3A9C9C6E90D8B.description:
Seek answers to questions during
play and daily activities using an
increasing variety of mathematical
strategies (figure out how to balance
a block structure; to build a bridge; to
create a pattern with Legos®).

9B1B9F9868574C9DB6BBF7F2ED9A4F6F.description:
Develop and
consistently use
intentional strategies
when working with
knobbed puzzles and
similar materials.

CA5473CBD53F48318944F2A3CD6CE291.description:
Use drawing and
concrete materials
to represent and
communicate
mathematical ideas (draw
many circles to show
“lots of people,” put craft
sticks in a pile to show the
number of children who
want crackers for snack).

E687E3288032435C93513000F5A9239E.description:
Seek answers to
questions by using
mathematical thinking (i.e.
reasoning and problem
solving) during play and
daily activities (determine
who is taller by standing
next to classmate; find
two smaller blocks to
replace larger block).

6C76D119705D4A91A1CAA0D33D03C8C2.description: Children use mathematical thinking to solve problems in their everyday environment.

92B01251AE3E40888F9F30D1F0A189F5.description:
Recognize routines with time passing
throughout the day (identifying circle
time, snack time, outside play, etc.).

E7F62AB67EC34C5BA7B0E74859A719B8.description:
Describe the weather as hot or cold.
(Continue to engage in explorations
with temperature).

78D7FA4C3B7B48C0963EDBC5D4BF56B3.description:
Use simple measurement tools with
guidance and support to informally
measure objects (a ruler, measuring
cup, scale).

2128FCF5E53047BF9CDFB6DF54F17257.description:
Put a few objects in order by size,
length or weight (arrange a group of 3
blocks in order from the shortest to the
longest).

7A90FABD0EB44845860F2FE70E700F22.description:
Directly compare more than two
objects by size, length, or weight (“That
rock is heavier than these others; I
can’t lift it.” Look at three strings that
are different lengths and select the
longest string).

B2F80B78DB5141D6B4227091FC93B91C.description:
Use descriptive language for size,
length, or weight (short, tall, long,
heavy, big).

D67338715C764AE2A49FDC81B6D5C32F.description:
Recognize routines with time
passing throughout the day
(identifying circle time, snack
time, outside play, etc.).

631F23C895E34D8895EA141101994E88.description: Describe the weather as hot or cold. (Engage in explorations with temperature).

FFD5603D32CD4394BEFA65DA5A6BA424.description: Use simple measurement tools with guidance and support to informally measure objects (a ruler, measuring cup, scale).

3DAFCAC93C2F44F0BE4409A4DF2A9E0F.description: Compare the size or weight of two objects and identify which one is longer/taller/ heavier than the other (“That rock is heavier than this one. I can lift it.” “The snake is longer than the worm”).

B4330C415D314CC8BAAFF0392DF36FBB.description: Use descriptive language for size, length, or weight (short, tall, long, heavy, big).

8B4E7578730F4CDD87DF6DBEF99DC022.description: Engage in continued explorations with temperature.

F8FE1D44744C480BB0862616434F7CED.description:
Use size and amount words to label and compare objects, people, and collections
(big truck, a lot of crackers, little baby).

8854E27CA702472EA556334402E062BB.description:
Engage in
beginning
explorations with
temperature (quickly
touching cold and
warm items).

5F36D7A55C8546ED9A5EBF0E41F3180A.description:
Participate in
activities that
compare the size
and weight of
objects.

F29152A86CF749E4A53341FDFD33A85F.description:
Examine
objects of
different sizes by
exploring (touch,
pick up, and
move objects).

5D7C576E35D84BD7BEFC189CB13EF881.description:
Children demonstrate a beginning understanding of measurement (the idea of repeating the use of an object to
measure) and a beginning understanding of data analysis through comparing and interpreting data during play and other activities.

B5870D7071214FCAB2351F3F991C1701.description: Foundations of Measurement and Data Analysis

C1429AA410E74FD8ACED614D8596E100.description:
Name basic 2 and 3-dimensional
shapes (square, prism, circle,
sphere, triangle, pyramid,
hexagon), and describe their
characteristics using informal
descriptive and geometric
attributes (“That’s a triangle; it’s
pointy.” “It’s a circle because it’s
round.”).

6D1FAE0AA0FE478DAE324B720D80B5C8.description:
Identify basic 2- and
3-dimensional shapes (square,
circle, triangle) in the environment.

091DAD8B19704039BB7A4C358BF43986.description:
Use 2- and 3-dimensional shapes
to represent real world objects
(say, “We are building a castle
and we need a round block for
the tunnel.” “I glued a circle and
a square on my picture to make a
house.”).

FD7DE80ACD554DE8B424B01D775F1B81.description:
Consistently use a variety of
words for positions in space (in,
on, over, under, etc.), and follow
directions using these words.

A67EE9CE832D4EB4ACBB68920E2E865E.description:
Stack or line up blocks
that are the same
shape.

288B9E4582E64A82A8E06E809520A5B8.description:
Name or match a few
2- and 3-dimensional
shapes (circle, sphere,
square, triangle, cone)
and describe their
differences.

91596C0488694629A967242ABFE20B70.description:
Respond to and begin
to use words describing
positions (in, on, over,
under, etc.).

B316A042B7324707A63A6EF4E6447845.description:
Stack or line up blocks
that are the same shape.

F80861716F954B309A4459118BF412C2.description:
Name or match a few
2- and 3-dimensional
shapes (circle, square,
cylinder).

3DC1FD73FBAA47EA996D2A413DE77D2A.description:
Respond to and
begin to use words
describing positions (in,
on, over, under, etc.).

FD3A3A4923C240F4A65011DD01737D5B.description:
Put basic shapes
into a shape sorter
using trial and error.

662206C2F3474B01ADC8077425A4BF5C.description:
Explore space with
their bodies (fit self
into large box, crawl
under table, climb
over low walls).

3B03C40D33FF42239649C87A23EB3687.description:
Attempt to put
objects into other
objects (such as
putting pieces into
holes or other
spaces).

7865EE9C0A8949AA9AF5BFFEC3FC9A13.description:
Examine different
shapes by
exploring (banging
blocks on the floor,
rolling balls).

50F4BE43B5714357BF35052B487CBBA7.description:
Children begin to identify, describe, classify, and understand shape, size, direction, and
movement during play and other activities.

3FCFCA7904E94DE196762FE95113EFC0.description: Foundations for Geometry and Spatial Understanding

21EE704828764E8A80C27B4D4400A358.description:
Show beginning abilities to
create simple repeating patterns.

4F1957B540054A9DBEBDC00374DA432B.description:
Describe, duplicate and extend
simple repeating patterns (twopart patterns) using concrete
objects (look at a pattern of
beads and tell what bead comes
next in the pattern).

142B8B607722462E9743D94B81BFDD0C.description:
Sort a group of objects (0-10)
using one attribute (color, size,
shape, quantity) with increasing
accuracy (sort blocks by shape
and place like-shaped blocks on
the shelf; sort beads by color or
another attribute).

AA45E35E06754BCE8ED86B1BD3ECA3CB.description:
Recognize simple
repeating patterns
(AB type patterns) and
attempt to repeat or
extend them during play
(repeat a movement
pattern during a song,
extend a line of blocks
in alternating colors).

8823F071AC3C413B8B5C2E374DB53F8D.description:
Identify familiar objects
as the same or different.

8FE0AF8E361A4A9A936C278A8B05BC0B.description:
Sort familiar objects into categories (cars with cars, plates separated from cups;
rectangle blocks on one
shelf and square blocks
on another).

40208AEC5CBC4D35AE73B20F7F526A9D.description:
Can follow along
and imitate patterns of
sounds and movement
(for example, repeating
a chorus in a song
or clapping a simple
rhythm).

DCC7EF99898E44B590584339AFC37F0A.description:
Sort familiar objects into categories (cars with cars, plates separated from cups;
rectangle blocks on
one shelf and square
blocks on another).

57B29FB15DFE44D59311FC427F2D10F7.description:
Can follow along
and imitate patterns
of sounds and
movement (for
example, repeating
a chorus in a song
or clapping a simple
rhythm).

13FF8AB93C86429B8166A1B86527DFF7.description:
Show awareness of
different categories
during play (put balls
in a box and dolls
in a bed; give one
friend all the cars
and another friend
all of the trucks when
playing in the block
area).

922C041348154084BA7942C0DA2FE732.description:
Children demonstrate a beginning understanding of algebraic thinking by sorting,
describing, extending, and creating simple patterns during play and other activities.

90BF5D071F1D44F78432C4EF3ADBED1B.description:
Show different ways a set
of up to five objects can be
decomposed (broken apart) or
composed (put together) (e.g.,
5 objects can be broken into 2
and 3 objects and 2 and 3 can
be combined to make 5 objects).

EEB0C6BF71874F629FC8E6AADAA37A02.description:
Use observation and counting with increasing accuracy to
answer questions such as “How
many do we need?” and “How
many more do we need?” during
play and other daily activities
(count new children to see how
many more plates are needed
for snack; return extra drinks to
cooler at picnic to arrive at the
correct number).

85F71F250AD7434B858D1B4720BBC804.description:
Show they understand
that putting objects
together in a set will
make a bigger set, and
removing objects from a
set will make a smaller
set.

65E559F86EDD483392280C3B88C6F377.description:
Use observation and
counting (not always
correctly) to find out
how many things are
needed during play and
other daily activities
(figure out how many
spoons are needed
for snack, find enough
dolls so each person
has one when playing in
the dramatic play area).

F8952FB99BA64D3D8AA589A7A5F0F86F.description:
Use observation and
emerging counting
skills (1, 2, 3) during
play and other daily
activities.

3764F26206DC43B5A8053B2E9AD0A6FB.description:
Children demonstrate a beginning understanding of numbers and operations during play
and other activities.

18CCC44C748C4E4CBE0035213C86D61F.description:
Show understanding of first, next, and last during play
and daily activities (answer questions about who is first
and last to slide down the slide; say, “The engine is first,
and the caboose is last” when making a train).

512CA01B186140589445CE2B93243D65.description:
Tell what number comes next or what number came
before another number when counting 1-5.

E155C99EEE23425B9F377CE9C293FCE3.description:
State the number of objects in a small collection (1-5)
without counting (when a friend holds up two fingers, look at
her hand and say, “Two fingers” without counting).

80C3F45114364A43A4F0FBFC8A827659.description: Given a number 0-5, count out that many objects.

DB21909B1A4B4BBFACAD548EFEC155D8.description:
Recognize that objects can be counted as part of
different groups (forks can be counted alone, or as part of
a set of utensils).

543F924D82594344B3CA461DF8086739.description:
Match numerals 1-10 to sets of objects, with guidance
and support.

6A13228DCABC464CA15BBD5CC6EE87E7.description:
Recognize numerals up to 10 and attempt to write them or
number-like forms during play and daily activities.

2A4F4BF468C84819A10EA19C7ADA7BF8.description:
Count up to 10 objects arranged in a line using oneto-one correspondence with increasing accuracy, and
answer the question “How many are there?”

AFA7AC89B6B34B6C82ECCC5F6E9D7EFF.description:
Count up to 10 objects in a variety of ways (for example,
left to right, right to left, in stacks, etc.).

4394C0387BCA4175915E266B06810E3F.description: Rote count to 20 with increasing accuracy.

D705C8F0E0B14AC081F03214FDADC6FA.description:
Show an understanding of magnitude by recognizing
larger sets when compared to smaller sets and describe
how they are different.

B391E786CE654992A15F2CA08BC8EC35.description:
Compare the amount of items in small sets of objects
(up to 5 objects) by matching or counting and use
language such as “more than” and “less than” to describe
the sets of objects.

57833764FF444F3094263F95D5E3276B.description:
Write numerals or numberlike forms up to 5 during play
and daily activities.

AED81F8E6CA745C8A24C0DF5AE684A33.description:
Match numerals 1-5 to sets
of objects, with guidance and
support.

F4437F59DB5048FEA3442758A91CB624.description:
Recognize numerals up
to 5 during play and daily
activities.

C499326999E2480C924CB65792434D9D.description:
Count up to 5 objects
arranged in a line using
one-to-one correspondence
with increasing accuracy and
answer the question, “How
many are there?”

B6A7B34D14234B838D8B1319270E3532.description:
Rote count to 10 with
increasing accuracy.

7538207DEE284D20815AA2FD8D9354F5.description:
Visually compare two
groups of objects that are
obviously equal or unequal
in quantity and communicate
that they are the same or
different, and, if appropriate,
which one has more and/
or which one has less. (If
child is offered two plates
of crackers can select the
preferred amount and can
explain that he wanted more
or less).

562045E8260F467E8765ABF53026A3F3.description:
Make a small group (1-3) with the
same number of items as another
group of items (take 3 balls from
a basket after the teacher shows
the group that she has 3 balls and
asks each person to take the same
number of balls)

B739592C96EC4944BFFE482DF37FC4D5.description:
Place items in one-to-one
correspondence during play and daily
routines (one spoon at each plate;
one doll in each toy car).

EAFFB4DB0795496AA6E91E8B190064A6.description:
Attempt to chant or recite numbers,
but not necessarily in the correct
order (for example, counting objects
on a page during a read aloud).

A1C8863AAC7C4D9C8587606B5DD0F8FC.description:
Recognize when presented with
two obviously unequal sets of objects
that one set has more than the other
and/or that one set has less than
the other. (Can point to which set of
crayons has more or less depending
on what is asked).

836C95B63FF945E7BC47226A77C6B060.description:
Use words or actions that show
understanding of the concepts of
“more,” “all,” and/or “none” (ask for
more food, stop asking for more
blocks when told they have “all” of
the blocks, become upset when told
there is no more Play-Doh®).

AED12925CA8941F88A0EE1E4B89123E7.description:
Recognize
when presented
with two
obviously
unequal sets of
objects that one
set has more
or less than the
other (Can point
to which set of
crayons has
more).

05B5710E31B24FCE9B8D8113C556E798.description:
Use words or
actions that show
understanding of
the concepts of
“more,” “less,”
and “all” (ask for
more food, stop
asking for more
blocks when told
they have “all”
of the blocks).

EF8AB4C5708C44C895F9EAF33EA2B8DD.description:
Explore quantity
(for example,
filling and
dumping
containers).

30651570D5244D4AB219E01C276B9239.description:
Show interest
(look at or
reach for)
in obvious
differences in
quantity (look
at a tower with
7 blocks longer
than a tower
with 3 blocks,
reach for a
basket with
three balls
rather than a
basket with one
ball).

C9432D2D38BA46C29D81F68D58157BEA.description:
Indicate they
want “more”
with signs,
sounds, or
looks.

4F3FE6D5C3B1431EAF853C1B1FB9C4DC.description: Children demonstrate a beginning understanding of numbers and quantity during play and other activities.
